Google today <a href="https://blog.google/products/pixel/pixel-9a-the-latest-a-series-phone-with-google-ai-smarts-at-an-unbeatable-value/">introduced</a> the Pixel 9a, its latest lower-priced smartphone. The device is launching in April, and it will compete with Apple's new iPhone 16e.<br/>
<br/>
<img src="https://images.macrumors.com/article-new/2025/03/Google-Pixel-9a.jpg" alt="" width="1600" height="900" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-995734" /><br/>
In terms of specs and pricing, the Pixel 9a tops the iPhone 16e in at least four ways.<br/>
<br/>
First, the Pixel 9a's 6.3-inch OLED display is larger than the iPhone 16e's 6.1-inch screen.<br/>
<br/>
Second, the Pixel 9a's display supports up to a 120Hz refresh rate for smoother scrolling and content, while the iPhone 16e is limited to 60Hz. <br/>
<br/>
Third, while both the Pixel 9a and the iPhone 16e are equipped with a 48-megapixel main rear camera, the Pixel 9a also has an Ultra Wide camera.<br/>
<br/>
Fourth, the Pixel 9a starts at &#36;499 in the U.S., while the iPhone 16e starts at &#36;599.<br/>
<br/>
Of course, the Pixel 9a runs Android, which is simply a dealbreaker for many iPhone users who prefer the Apple ecosystem or feel too locked in to bother switching platforms. But, increased competition is always good to see.<br/>
<br/>
